{"id":"d=origam-topic-4292//p=08663cbc448b4913bdee45880b2ca126","tags":{"__document_id":["origam-topic-4292"],"__file_type":["text/plain"],"__file_id":["f0c3fe2540664e2bbfa4aca74255d561"],"__file_part":["49af2c601e6b49adbd49bc44a1860c5a"],"__part_n":["5"],"__sect_n":["0"],"source":["origam-community"],"topicId":["4292"],"categoryId":["61"],"url":["https://community.origam.com/t/how-to-create-a-simple-api/4292"],"title":["How to create a simple API"],"imagesFound":["11"],"imagesDescribed":["11"],"imageUrl":["https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/6/61998b38f8e87b432e3af027ce3731715c4379de.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/5/56824411524bc539cdae5a3706feb4bdf0f21949.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/c/ce7f6066dee18e15bafa83859897c226c280aea3.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/0/0c9a57351628e3b091abeb06b138acc67087a1b1.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/6/6a3a62494f76ceaaf305ce02ef5e18b3c321e2b9.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/e/e89d2c81c195265fc16c763626092191d2db502d.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/0/054e94792a151767ed94e95b09ccaa5bc0ca7b6e.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/5/59242013445428e7aa2804e0fe78bb69aa65c3fa.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/5/5d9473b1e0697bbdab335431c05e8fd7ed36b0de.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/1/145ae915189682a86f73d433417bd08a3e3665a4.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/7/7bead95d6c06ae8fb555e485d26467a583b63b7d.png"]},"payload":{"url":"","schema":"20231218A","file":"content.txt","text":"\u0022 section appears without specified entries. On the right side, the \u0022Model Browser\u0022 shows a hierarchical structure with categories like \u0022Common,\u0022 \u0022Data,\u0022 \u0022User Interface,\u0022 \u0022Business Logic,\u0022 and \u0022API.\u0022 Under \u0022API,\u0022 it lists \u0022Web API/Pages\u0022 with paths for \u0022admin/addUser\u0022 and \u0022api/public/tasks,\u0022 indicating the application is related to web API development and task management functionalities. The overall context suggests a tool for configuring API tasks and parameter mappings within a software application.\n\n\n  \n Include the complete record structure in the request body \u2014 exactly as returned by the GET command, including all brackets and  \u0022ROOT\u0022 , for example: \n \n  {\n  \u0022ROOT\u0022: {\n    \u0022Task\u0022: [\n      {\n        \u0022Status_Id\u0022: \u0022376ae614-1381-4ff5-b894-9c96c7978ead\u0022,\n        \u0022Name\u0022: \u0022Create accounts\u0022,\n        \u0022AssignedTo_Id\u0022: \u002221c7c5cd-b373-43a6-aa40-aed4533686c2\u0022,\n        \u0022DueDate\u0022: \u00222025-11-30T00:00:00\u002B01:00\u0022,\n        \u0022Priority_Id\u0022: \u0022bae03329-491c-4b09-8345-f8d26f027e9b\u0022,\n        \u0022NotificationSent\u0022: false,\n        \u0022Description\u0022: \u0022Create user accounts for all new users who joined this month\u0022,\n        \u0022Selected\u0022: false,\n        \u0022RecordCreated\u0022: \u00222025-02-18T13:56:18.073\u002B01:00\u0022,\n        \u0022RecordUpdatedBy\u0022: \u002221c7c5cd-b373-43a6-aa40-aed4533686c2\u0022,\n        \u0022Id\u0022: \u00225784a17e-15fe-4f1e-b612-6a35055f4c0c\u0022,\n        \u0022RecordCreatedBy\u0022: \u002221c7c5cd-b373-43a6-aa40-aed4533686c2\u0022,\n        \u0022RecordUpdated\u0022: \u00222025-11-06T10:10:30.447\u002B01:00\u0022\n      }\n    ]\n  }\n}\n  \n \n   If you include only some fields in the request body, the remaining fields will be set to  null  or lost. Therefore, if you intend to update only specific fields (similar to a PATCH request), you must still provide the full record data and modify only the fields you wish to change. \n \n   Delete a record \n To enable record deletion via the API, set  AllowDELETE  to  True  in your API configuration. \n When a DELETE request with a valid Id is sent, the corresponding record will be deleted. \nFor example, this request: \n DELETE https://localhost/api/public/task/5784a17e-15fe-4f1e-b612-6a35055f4c0c  \nwill delete the record with that Id, if it exists. No request body is required. \n   Other API types \n In addition to the content above, several other types of APIs are listed below: \n  Workflow Page  \n\n---\n\n@vikter (2026-04-09 13:53:05Z):\n   Workflow Page API type \n This type of API is used to trigger a  sequential workflow  in the application. The settings are similar to the Data Page type but here is also a specification of the workflow that this function is supposed to trigger: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/7/7bead95d6c06ae8fb555e485d26467a583b63b7d.png]\nDescription: The image depicts a user interface for a Workflow Page titled \u0022api/private/allotment/changes.\u0022 It includes various sections such as (Info), InputValidation, Misc, Page, Security, and Updating. Key visible text includes \u0022Schema Item,\u0022 \u0022Name,\u0022 \u0022MimeType,\u0022 \u0022Url,\u0022 \u0022Roles,\u0022 \u0022AllowDELETE,\u0022 \u0022AllowPUT,\u0022 and \u0022Workflow.\u0022 Under the InputValidation section, \u0022DisableConstraintForInputValidation\u0022 is set to False, and there is an \u0022InputValidationRule.\u0022 The Page section specifies \u0022application/json\u0022 as the MimeType. The Updating section indicates that AllowDELETE is set to False and AllowPUT is set to True. The Workflow listed is \u0022Allotment_Update,\u0022 suggesting that this page is intended for managing updates related to allotments via an API.\n\n\n  \n Data can also be passed to this workflow via parameter mapping. For example, JSON is passed here as  InputData , which is then stored in the workflow\u2019s context store for further use:","vector_provider":"AI.Ollama.OllamaTextEmbeddingGenerator","vector